article.headline: Spurs led by as many as 30
article.linkText: Spurs rough up Sonics for 7th straight win
article.story:
SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- The San Antonio Spurs aren't making it easy for the Minnesota Timberwolves in the Midwest Division. The Spurs, led by Tim Duncan's 21 points and 10 rebounds, pulled within a game of the division-leading Timberwolves by posting a 96-75 victory over Seattle on Wednesday night. Both San Antonio and Minnesota have four games remaining. The Timberwolves face a tough test on Thursday at Sacramento, currently the top seed in the Western Conference. The Spurs play two of their final games against Portland, which has scrapped back into contention for the eighth seed in the West. "They've got good chemistry," San Antonio coach Gregg Popovich said of the Trail Blazers. "I think they are playing as well as anybody in the league right now. ... They're going to be a big challenge for us." The SuperSonics, long out of the playoff picture, didn't present much of a challenge for the Spurs, who won their seventh straight overall and their 10th straight at home. They ran off a 19-4 burst early in the second half after leading 46-36 at the break. San Antonio's lead grew to as many as 30 early in the fourth quarter. "The offense is working for us," Duncan said. "Everybody is shooting the ball, getting wide-open shots, because we're moving the ball so well." The defense was also working on Wednesday -- Seattle shot only 35.5 percent from the floor. The worst came for the Sonics in the third, when they made only two field goals. San Antonio scored 31 points in the third, 20 of them inside. "They basically just dominated the paint," said Seattle coach Nate McMillan, whose team has now dropped six of its last seven games. "When they have a lead they can be patient in their offensive sets and get the look they want." Tony Parker and Hedo Turkoglu each scored 14 points for San Antonio, while Rasho Nesterovic had 10 points and 10 rebounds. Ray Allen paced the SuperSonics with 17 points, and Ansu Sesay had 13 and Luke Ridnour 12. Allen shot 6-for-16 while being defended mostly by perimeter specialist Bruce Bowen, whose scrappy, annoying style he labeled "sissy basketball" after a loss to the Spurs earlier in the season. The Sonics played without Rashard Lewis, the team's top rebounder and No. 2 scorer. Lewis suffered a left hip flexor and left knee bruise in his team's 118-108 loss at Dallas on Tuesday. Duncan and Turkoglu combined for seven baskets early in the third period as the Spurs went on their decisive run. Vitaly Potapenko scored Seattle's first basket of the quarter at 7:40, and the other came three minutes later by Sesay. "For any team in the league it's tough to play two of the best teams back to back," Sesay said. "We had a good game in Dallas, but tonight we just didn't have it." The Spurs were running toward a rout in the game's early minutes. They scored on all but one of their first 10 possessions, the last being a powerful two-handed dunk by Duncan that made the score 19-5. Trailing by 10 to start the second quarter, Seattle took advantage of a string of San Antonio turnovers to cut the difference to 31-30 with seven minutes until halftime. Allen hit a 3-pointer and two layups on successive trips and then Antonio Daniels made a driving layup. Duncan followed with a jumper to start a 9-2 Spurs run, and he finished the half with a dunk and a layup.

Game notes
Duncan had not led the Spurs in scoring in the past four games ... Seattle signed F Leon Smith to a 10-day contract on Tuesday. Smith, drafted out of high school by the Spurs in 1999, scored two points in four minutes. ... The Spurs host the Trail Blazers on Friday and then the teams meet again in Portland on Monday.
